ast=Lewis|first=George E.|title=Special issue on Technology and Black Music in the Americas|journal=Journal of the Society for American Music|year=2008|volume=2|issue=2|url=http://journals.cambridge.org/action/displayIssue?jid=SAM&volumeId=2&issueId=02}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Mayer |first=Ruth |year=2000 |jstor=41157608 |title='Africa As an Alien Future': The Middle Passage, Afrofuturism, and Postcolonial Waterworlds |journal=Amerikastudien / American Studies |volume=45 |issue=4 |pages=555\u2013566}}\n* Nelson, Alondra (Spring 2000). \"Afrofuturism: Past-Future Visions.\" Color Lines: 34\u201337.\n* {{cite book|editor=Nelson, Alondra|title=Afrofuturism: A Special Issue of Social Text|date=June 3, 2002|publisher=Duke University Press|isbn=978-0822365457}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.authorsden.com/visit/viewarticle.asp?AuthorID=7174&id=4308 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030829011720/http://www.authorsden.com/visit/viewarticle.asp?AuthorID=7174&id=4308 |url-status=dead |archive-date=August 29, 2003 |title=What is Afrofuturism? |last=Rockeymoore |first=Mark A. |date=February 27, 2002 |work=[[AuthorsDen]] |accessdate=January 16, 2014 }}\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.slate.com/articles/arts/culturebox/2008/06/lil_wayne_and_the_afronaut_invasion.html|title=Lil Wayne, Tha Carter III, and the Afronaut invasion|last=Weiner|first=Jonah|date=June 20, 2008|work=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]|accessdate=16 January 2014}}\n* {{cite book|last=Williams|first=Ben|editor=Nelson|title=Technicolor: Race, Technology, and Everyday Life|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=s93SFzmc2psC&pg=PA154|year=2001|publisher=NYU Press|isbn=9780814736043|pages=[https://archive.org/details/technicolorracet0000unse/page/154 154\u2013176]|chapter=Black Secret Technology: Detroit Techno and the Information Age|display-editors=etal|url=https://archive.org/details/technicolorracet0000unse/page/154}}\n* {{cite book |last=Thomas |first=Sheree |authorlink=Sheree Thomas |editor-first=Sheree |editor-last=Thomas |title=Dark Matter: A Century of Speculative Fiction from the African Diaspora |year=2000 |publisher=Warner Aspect |isbn=0446525839 |url=https://archive.org/details/darkmattercentur00thom }} [[Dark Matter (series)|Dark Matter]]\n* {{cite book |last=Thomas |first=Sheree|authorlink=Sheree Thomas |editor-first=Sheree |editor-last=Thomas |title=Dark Matter: Reading the Bones |year=2004|publisher=Warner Aspect |isbn=0446693774}} ''[[Dark Matter (series)|Dark Matter: Reading the Bones]]''\n* {{cite book|last=Womack|first=Ytasha|title=Afrofuturism: The World of Black Sci-Fi and Fantasy Culture|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HTvVAAAAQBAJ|date=2013-10-01|publisher=Chicago Review Press|isbn=9781613747964}}\n* {{cite journal|last=Yaszek|first=Lisa|year=2005|title=An Afrofuturist Reading of Ralph Ellison's ''Invisible Man''|journal=[[Rethinking History]]|volume=9|issue=2\u20133|pages=297\u2013313|issn=1364-2529|doi=10.1080/13642520500149202}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://afrofuturism.net Afrofuturism.net]\n* [http://www.oxfordbibliographies.com/view/document/obo-9780190221911/obo-9780190221911-0004.xml Afrofuturism \u2013 Literary and Critical Theory \u2013 Oxford Bibliographies]\n* [http://blackstothefuture.com Black(s) to the Future \u2013 French]\n{{African American topics}}\n{{Science fiction}}\n{{Speculative fiction all}}\n\n[[Category:Afrofuturism| ]]\n[[Category:Art movements]]\n[[Category:African-American culture]]\n[[Category:Science fiction genres]]\n[[Category:Futurism by region]]\n[[Category:African diaspora literature]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toTricky(link changed toTricky (musician)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Afrofuturism"}
{"title_page": "Scott Partridge", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2017}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Scott Partridge\n| image = \n| fullname = Scott Malcolm Partridge<ref>{{Hugman|id=15375|accessdate=11 January 2020}}</ref>\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1974|10|13|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Leicester]], England\n| height = {{height|ft=5|in=9}}<ref name=\"Soccerbase\" />\n| position = [[Forward (association football)|Forward]], [[Midfielder#Winger|Winger]]\n| youthyears1 = \n| youthclubs1 = [[Grimsby Town F.C.|Grimsby Town]]\n| youthyears2 = {{0|0000}}\u20131992\n| youthclubs2 = [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]]\n| years1 = 1992\u20131994\n| years2 = 1994\u20131997\n| years3 = 1995\n| years4 = 1996\n| years5 = 1996\n| years6 = 1997\u20131998\n| years7 = 1998\u20131999\n| years8 = 1999\u20132001\n| years9 = 2001\u20132003\n| years10 = 2003\n| years11 = 2003\n| years12 = 2003\u20132004\n| years13 = 2004\u20132008\n| years14 = 2008\n| years15 = 2008\u20132009\n| clubs1 = [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]]\n| clubs2 = [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]]\n| clubs3 = \u2192 [[Torquay United F.C.|Torquay United]] (loan)\n| clubs4 = \u2192 [[Plymouth Argyle F.C.|Plymouth Argyle]] (loan)\n| clubs5 = \u2192 [[Scarborough F.C.|Scarborough]] (loan)\n| clubs6 = [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]]\n| clubs7 = [[Torquay United F.C.|Torquay United]]\n| clubs8 = [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]]\n| clubs9 = [[Rushden and Diamonds F.C.|Rushden & Diamonds]]\n| clubs10 = \u2192 [[Exeter City F.C.|Exeter City]] (loan)\n| clubs11 = [[Shrewsbury Town F.C.|Shrewsbury Town]]\n| clubs12 = [[Weymouth F.C.|Weymouth]]\n| clubs13 = [[Bath City F.C.|Bath City]]\n| clubs14 = [[Sheffield F.C.|Sheffield]]\n| clubs15 = [[Weston-super-Mare A.F.C.|Weston-super-Mare]]\n| caps1 = 5\n| caps2 = 57\n| caps3 = 5\n| caps4 = 7\n| caps5 = 7\n| caps6 = 36\n| caps7 = 34\n| caps8 = 93\n| caps9 = 44\n| caps10 = 4\n| caps11 = 4\n| caps12 = 14\n| caps13 = 138\n| caps14 = 23\n| caps15 = 9\n| goals1 = 0\n| goals2 = 7\n| goals3 = 2\n| goals4 = 2\n| goals5 = 0\n| goals6 = 2\n| goals7 = 13\n| goals8 = 21\n| goals9 = 5\n| goals10 = 2\n| goals11 = 0\n| goals12 = 2\n| goals13 = 68\n| goals14 = 19\n| goals15 = 0\n| totalcaps = 480\n| totalgoals = 143\n}}\n'''Scott Malcolm Partridge''' (born 13 October 1974) is an English retired professional [[association football|football]] [[Forward (association football)|forward]] who played in the [[Football League]], most notably for [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]]. In a nomadic league career, he also played for [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]], [[Rushden & Diamonds F.C.|Rushden & Diamonds]], [[Torquay United F.C.|Torquay United]], [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]], [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]], [[Plymouth Argyle F.C.|Plymouth Argyle]], [[Scarborough F.C.|Scarborough]] and [[Exeter City F.C.|Exeter City]]. He was described as \"an immensely skilful little striker with a wonderful first touch\", while \"rarely getting the goals his contribution deserved\".<ref name=\"BBB90s\" />\n\n==Career==\n\n=== Early years ===\nA [[Forward (association football)|forward]], Partridge began his career in the [[youth system]] at [[Grimsby Town F.C.|Grimsby Town]], before moving to [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]] and signing his first professional contract in July 1992.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.11v11.com/players/scott-partridge-4330/ |title=Scott Partridge |website=11v11.com |access-date=25 December 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"grecianarchive\">{{Cite web |url=http://grecianarchive.exeter.ac.uk/items/show/454 |title=Patridge, Scott \u2013 The Grecian Archive |website=grecianarchive.exeter.ac.uk |language=en-US |access-date=25 December 2017}}</ref> He made just five first team substitute appearances for the Bantams,<ref name=\"grecianarchive\" /> before moving to [[Football League First Division|First Division]] club [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]] on a [[Free transfer (association football)|free transfer]] on 18 February 1994.<ref name=\"Soccerbase\" /> He made something of a breakthrough at [[Ashton Gate Stadium|Ashton Gate]], making 66 appearances and scoring eight goals over the course of three seasons, but was forced to spend time away on [[Loan (sports)|loan]] during the [[1995\u201396 Football League|1995\u201396]] season.<ref name=\"Soccerbase\" /> Partridge joined [[Football League Third Division|Third Division]] club [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]] for a \u00a350,000 fee in February 1997, but after 13 months in which he was mainly utilised as a [[Midfielder#Winger|Winger]],<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/incoming/gallery/cardiff-city-rejects-who-proved-8460309 |title=Cardiff City rejects who proved the Bluebirds wrong |last=Rogers |first=Gareth |date=16 January 2015 |work=walesonline |access-date=25 December 2017}}</ref> he departed [[Ninian Park]] in March 1998, having made 41 appearances and scored just two goals.<ref name=\"Soccerbase\" />\n\n=== Torquay United ===\nOn 26 March 1998, Partridge returned to Third Division club [[Torquay United F.C.|Torquay United]] (with whom he had previously had a loan spell during the [[1995\u201396 Torquay United F.C. season|1995\u201396]] season) on a free transfer.<ref name=\"BBB90s\">{{Cite book |title=The Big Brentford Book Of The Nineties |last=Croxford |first=Mark |last2=Lane |first2=David |last3=Waterman |first3=Greville |publisher=Legends Publishing |year=2013 |isbn=9781906796723 |location=Sunbury, Middlesex |pages=436\u2013437}}</ref><ref name=\"Soccerbase\" /> Despite failing to score in each of his five appearances at the end of the [[1997\u201398 Football League Third Division|1997\u201398]] season,<ref name=\"Soccerbase9798\" /> Partridge finally found his goalscoring touch during [[1998\u201399 Football League Third Division|1998\u201399]], scoring 14 goals in 35 matches before departing [[Plainmoor]] in February 1999.<ref name=\"Soccerbase9899\" />\n\n=== Brentford ===\nPartridge joined high-flying Third Division club [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]] for a \u00a3100,000 fee on 19 February 1999.<ref name=\"BBB90s\" /> Paired with [[Lloyd Owusu]] in attack,<ref name=\"Timeless\">{{Cite book |title=Timeless Bees: Brentford F.C. Who's Who 1920\u20132006 |last=Haynes |first=Graham |last2=Coumbe |first2=Frank |publisher=Yore Publications |year=2006 |isbn=0955294916 |location=Harefield |page=121}}</ref> he showed excellent form in what remained of the [[1998\u201399 Brentford F.C. season|1998\u201399]] season, scoring seven goals in 14 matches to help the Bees to the Third Division title after victory over the eventual runners-up [[Cambridge United F.C.|Cambridge United]] on the final day.<ref name=\"Soccerbase9899\" /><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.statto.com/football/teams/brentford/1998-1999/results |title=Brentford results for the 1998-1999 season - Statto.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160426234542/http://www.statto.com/football/teams/brentford/1998-1999/results |archive-date=26 April 2016 |url-status=dead |access-date=25 December 2017}}</ref> Back in the [[Football League Second Division|Second Division]], Partridge scored four goals in an eight-match spell between late August and early September 1999, but scored just twice more to finish a mid-table season with 47 appearances and six goals.<ref name=\"Soccerbase9900\" /><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.statto.com/football/teams/brentford/history |title=Brentford Complete History - Statto.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304061629/http://www.statto.com/football/teams/brentford/history |archive-date=4 March 2016 |url-status=dead |access-date=25 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nPartridge began the [[2000\u201301 Brentford F.C. season|2000\u201301]] season on the bench, but regained his starting place under [[caretaker manager]] [[Ray Lewington]] in December 2000.<ref name=\"Timeless\" /><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/b/brentford/1032360.stm |title=Noades resigns as Brentford boss |date=20 November 2000 |access-date=25 December 2017 |language=en-GB}}</ref> Paired again with Lloyd Owusu, he scored 9 goals between December and the end of the season, to finish with 47 appearances and 10 goals.<ref name=\"Soccerbase0001\" /> The 2000\u201301 season was memorable for Brentford's run to the [[2001 Football League Trophy Final|final]] of the [[Football League Trophy]], though despite playing the full 90 minutes at the [[Millennium Stadium]], the Bees were beaten 2\u20131 by [[Port Vale F.C.|Port Vale]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/1289338.stm |title=Vale vault Brentford to lift Vans trophy |date=22 April 2001 |access-date=25 December 2017 |language=en-GB}}</ref> New manager [[Steve Coppell]]'s signing of forward [[Ben Burgess]] on loan in August 2001 heralded the beginning of the end of Partridge's time at [[Griffin Park]] and after two early [[2001\u201302 Brentford F.C. season|2001\u201302]] season appearances,<ref name=\"Soccerbase0102\" /> he departed the club in September 2001.<ref name=\"Soccerbase\" /> During two-and-a-half seasons with Brentford, Partridge made 110 appearances and scored 23 goals.<ref name=\"Soccerbase\" />\n\n===Rushden & Diamonds ===\nPartridge dropped back down to the Third Division to join newly promoted [[Rushden & Diamonds F.C.|Rushden & Diamonds]] on a free transfer on 14 September 2001.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.northamptonchron.co.uk/news/partridge-flies-high-1-934676 |title=Partridge flies high |website=www.northamptonchron.co.uk |language=en |access-date=25 December 2017}}</ref> Aside from a spell of five goals in 12 matches between late October and late December 2001, Partridge failed to recapture any goalscoring form,<ref name=\"Soccerbase0102\" /> but did help the team to the [[2002 Football League Third Division play-off Final|2002 Third Division play-off Final]], which was lost 3\u20131 to [[Cheltenham Town F.C.|Cheltenham Town]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_3/1967943.stm |title=Cheltenham crack Diamonds |date=6 May 2002 |access-date=25 December 2017 |language=en-GB}}</ref> He was utilised almost exclusively as a substitute in the early months of the [[2002\u201303 Football League Third Division|2002\u201303]] season,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.espnfc.com/player/5962/scott-partridge |title=Scott Partridge Player Profile \u2013 ESPN FC |website=www.espnfc.com |access-date=25 December 2017}}</ref> before being [[transfer-list]]ed in December 2002.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/r/rushden_and_diamonds/2566489.stm |title=Rushden release duo |date=11 December 2002 |access-date=25 December 2017 |language=en-GB}}</ref> Partridge departed [[Nene Park]] on 26 March 2003 and made 52 appearances and scored five goals for the club.<ref name=\"A-Z\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.thediamondsfc.com.p.preprod.performgroup.com/page/A-ZofDiamonds/0,,10784~1259616,00.html |title=Rushden & Diamonds {{!}} Club {{!}} A-Z of Diamonds {{!}} A-Z of Diamonds {{!}} Scott Partridge |website=www.thediamondsfc.com |url-status=dead |access-date=12 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n====Exeter City (loan) ====\nOn 31 December 2002, Partridge joined Third Division club [[Exeter City F.C.|Exeter City]] on a one-month loan.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/2552177.stm |title=Transfers \u2013 December 2002 |date=7 December 2002 |access-date=25 December 2017 |language=en-GB}}</ref> He scored in each of his first two matches and made four appearances before his loan expired,<ref name=\"Soccerbase0203\">{{Soccerbase season|id=6137|season=2002|access-date=24 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/e/exeter_city/2725719.stm |title=Partridge exits St James |date=4 February 2003 |access-date=25 December 2017 |language=en-GB}}</ref> despite attempts by manager [[Neil McNab]] to persuade him to stay.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/e/exeter_city/2706715.stm |title=McNab keen on Partridge |date=2003 |access-date=25 December 2017 |language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n=== Shrewsbury Town ===\nOn 27 March 2003, Partridge joined Third Division club [[Shrewsbury Town F.C.|Shrewsbury Town]] on a contract running until the end of the 2002\u201303 season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://world.shrewsburytown.com.p.preprod.performgroup.com/page/NewsDetail/0,,10443~363857,00.html |title=Shrewsbury Town {{!}} News {{!}} Latest {{!}} Latest {{!}} Transfer Day signings |date=27 March 2003 |website=shrewsburytown.com |url-status=dead |access-date=9 April 2018}}</ref> He made just four appearances before his contract expired.<ref name=\"Soccerbase0203\" />\n\n=== Non-league football ===\n[[Weymouth F.C.|Weymouth]] [[player-manager]] [[Steve Claridge]] made Partridge his first signing of the [[2003\u201304 Southern Football League|2003\u201304]] season and he signed a three-year contract.<ref name=\"dorsetecho\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.dorsetecho.co.uk/news/5371052.EXIT_FOR_PARTRIDGE/?ref=arc |title=EXIT FOR PARTRIDGE |website=Dorset Echo |language=en |access-date=26 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.dorsetecho.co.uk/news/5378112.DIAMOND_GEEZER/ |title=DIAMOND GEEZER |website=Dorset Echo |language=en |access-date=25 December 2017}}</ref> He scored 11 goals in 30 appearances before being allowed to join [[Southern Football League|Southern League]] Premier Division rivals [[Bath City F.C.|Bath City]] on a free transfer on 9 January 2004.<ref name=\"dorsetecho\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://theterras.com/index.php/weymouth-football-club-archive/player-archive/|title=Player Archive|work=THE TERRAS|access-date=24 January 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref> Partridge went on to have a successful four-and-a-half season spell at [[Twerton Park]], with a pinnacle being the title-winning [[2006\u201307 Southern Football League|2006\u201307]] season, which secured promotion to the [[Conference South]].<ref name=\"soccerfacts0607\" /><ref name=\"FCHD\" /> After recovering from a neck injury, he played on until March 2008, before departing the club to look after his mother.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.bathcityfc.com/march-2008/ |title=Family illness sees Scott Partridge depart Twerton Park (13/3/08) |website=old.bathcityfc.com |accessdate=26 December 2017}}</ref> Partridge joined [[Northern Premier League]] First Division South club [[Sheffield F.C.|Sheffield]] in 2008,<ref name=\"ConfsouthBath\" /> but moved back up to the Conference South to join [[Weston-super-Mare A.F.C.|Weston-super-Mare]] on 31 December 2008 and made 9 appearances before retiring at the end of the [[2008\u201309 Football Conference|2008\u201309]] season.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.westonsupermareafc.co.uk/news.asp#552 |title=Partridge lands in Seagulls nest |date=31 December 2008 |access-date=1 January 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090201171211/http://www.westonsupermareafc.co.uk/news.asp#552 |archive-date=1 February 2009 |publisher=Weston-super-Mare F.C.}}</ref><ref name=\"ConfsouthWeston\" />\n\n== Personal life ==\nPartridge's father, [[Malcolm Partridge|Malcolm]], was also a professional footballer.<ref>{{Cite book |title=TW8: Brentford Official Matchday Programme versus Walsall 28/10/00 |publisher=Morganprint |year=2000 |location=Charlton, London |page=14}}</ref> As of January 2004, he was living in [[Bristol]].<ref name=\"dorsetecho\" />\n\n==Honours==\n'''Brentford'''\n* [[Football League Third Division]]: [[1998\u201399 Brentford F.C. season|1998\u201399]]<ref name=\"Soccerbase9899\" />\n'''Rushden & Diamonds'''\n*Conference Shield: 2001<ref name=\"Soccerbase0102\">{{Soccerbase season|id=6137|season=2001|access-date=24 December 2017}}</ref>\n'''Weymouth'''\n*[[Southern Football League|Southern League]] Premier Division second-place promotion: [[2003\u201304 Southern Football League|2003\u201304]]<ref name=\"soccerfacts0304\">{{Cite web |url=http://soccerfactsuk.co.uk/s2003/player_details.php?playerid=1898 |title=SoccerFacts UK Player Details |website=soccerfactsuk.co.uk |access-date=24 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Fchd|id=WEYMOUTH|name=Weymouth F.C.}}</ref>\n'''Bath City'''\n* Southern League Premier Division: [[2006\u201307 Southern Football League|2006\u201307]]<ref name=\"soccerfacts0607\">{{Cite web |url=http://soccerfactsuk.co.uk/s2006/player_details.php?playerid=4406 |title=SoccerFacts UK Player Details |website=soccerfactsuk.co.uk |access-date=24 December 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"FCHD\">{{Fchd|id=BATHC|name=Bath City F.C.}}</ref>\n\n'''Individual'''\n\n* [[FA Cup]] Player of the Round: Third qualifying round, [[2004\u201305 FA Cup qualifying rounds|2004\u201305]]<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/fa_cup/3952803.stm |title=Partridge wins FA Cup award |date=25 October 2004 |access-date=25 December 2017 |language=en-GB}}</ref>\n* Team of the FA Cup: [[2004\u201305 FA Cup|2004\u201305]]<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/fa_cup/4258632.stm |title=Laidlaw wins FA Cup player award |date=19 September 2005 |access-date=25 December 2017 |language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n== Career statistics ==\n{{Expand section|\n* Cup appearances in non-league football|date=December 2017}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Club\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Season\n! colspan=\"3\" |League\n! colspan=\"2\" |FA Cup\n! colspan=\"2\" |League Cup\n! colspan=\"2\" |Other\n! colspan=\"2\" |Total\n|-\n!Division\n!Apps\n!Goals\n!Apps\n!Goals\n!Apps\n!Goals\n!Apps\n!Goals\n!Apps\n!Goals\n|-\n|[[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]]\n! colspan=\"2\" |Total\n!5\n!0\n!0\n!0\n!2\n!0\n!0\n!0\n!7\n!0\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]]\n|[[1996\u201397 Bristol City F.C. season|1996\u201397]]<ref name=\"Soccerbase9697\">{{Soccerbase season|id=6137|season=1996|access-date=24 